presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bilateral breast involvement with diffuse pain","Multiple small, cold abscesses throughout the breast","Nipple discharge without associated inflammation","Painless, firm masses in both breasts","Unilateral, localised inflammation with erythema and warmth"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe typical presentation of mastitis is \u003Cstrong\u003Eunilateral, localised inflammation with erythema and warmth\u003C/strong\u003E. The affected area is tender and may be accompanied by systemic symptoms such as fever and malaise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral breast involvement with diffuse pain\u003C/strong\u003E - Mastitis is typically unilateral; bilateral involvement is uncommon\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple small, cold abscesses throughout the breast\u003C/strong\u003E - While mastitis can progress to form an abscess, multiple cold abscesses are not characteristic\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPainless, firm masses in both breasts\u003C/strong\u003E - Mastitis is typically painful and inflammatory rather than presenting as painless masses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENipple discharge without associated inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - Inflammation is a key feature of mastitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMastitis commonly occurs in lactating women due to milk stasis and bacterial infection, most frequently caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. The condition typically develops in the first 6-12 weeks postpartum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mastitis typically presents as a unilateral, localised area of breast inflammation with erythema, warmth, swelling and tenderness.","Mastitis most commonly affects lactating women in the first 6-12 weeks postpartum due to milk stasis and bacterial infection.","Staphylococcus aureus is the most common causative organism in lactational mastitis."],"references":["Blackmon MM, Nguyen H, Mukherji P. Acute Mastitis. [Updated 2023 Jul 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557782/","Pevzner M, Dahan A. Mastitis While Breastfeeding: Prevention, the Importance of Proper Treatment, and Potential Complications. J Clin Med. 2020 Jul 22;9(8):2328. doi: 10.3390/jcm9082328. PMID: 32707832; PMCID: PMC7465810","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52068"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16201"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52068"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T16:02:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T16:03:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8892"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66615"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},